Course.Notes: Start on paved road above Steeplechase Grandstand. Turn left at the split. At second split, turn left onto trail. Continue on trail to end at Old Hickory Blvd. Turn left on Park Rd. Turn right at split, then right on Vaughn Rd. After 50 yards, turn left onto the Steeplechase field. Go straight through the two gates of the main track, then right following the fence at 12 feet distance. At the second cedar tree turn left towards the gravel road. Continue on this road to the end, then left and left to connect with another gravel road. Take second road down the hill. Finish at the single tree with horse jump.

Dan and Brian joined me today. Definitely changed the intensity of the workout. I'd call it Dan intensity as he led most of the time. 4 total hills and sprints. Of the hills, I made it up aaaalmost to the top the first 2 times, but I was fried on the 3rd, and the last I paced myself and made it up all the way. Of the sprints, the third was really all out with me and Dan neck and neck. Brian slugged it out through 3 circuits and then called it quits. He never stopping to walk or take a breather like me.
Things I learned:
1. I'm a wuss! Both Dan (sub 5 miler) and Bryan (sub 3hr marathoner) seem like guys who really like pushing the pace. I need to get there, too. 2. Although, I've probably put int more miles this week than they have so I still feel like I held my own. 3. I need to get used to the stress involved in high intensity workouts in a group. I don't care about heaving in front of someone, but I sure don't want to get an asthma attack at the wrong time.

Longest distance run in over six weeks (I think). Also faster than the 2 mile time trial just two days ago. Did have to stop twice on shale hill, but made up for it by having enough of a kick and passing a runner near the finish line who had passed me on the way up the hill.
I could tell that my legs need more distance training... they felt a little tight and full, and I had a thought that I didn't want to get injured via compartment syndrome.
Still need to focus more on tightening the core and using quads and hams more than feet. Left foot really felt really wobbly, and I could tell that it threw off my knee stability. I seem to really land on the far outside of my left foot, which then jars it into a pronated position. That's probably why my inside ankle muscles get pulled and sore.
It's harder than you think to trick your brain into moving your body faster than it wants. It's as if I'm standing next to my real self and watching myself perform. I may tell myself that I should go faster at this point in the race or not stop going up the hill, but I seem to ignore that self talk and just do what it seems I'm programmed to do... slow down and stop. The good thing about today is that I didn't view the stopping and the slowing down in a negative way. Heck, I contacted mono just six weeks ago and haven't run consistently at all! So I actually feel good about the race. I was happy to be out there in the cold and the rain. When I stopped at shale hill, I marvelled at the apperance of the gray bluff... it's really quite beautiful if you stop and think about it. After the race I also made a point to admire the view from the road atop steeple chase. Beautiful!

I tried very hard to feel what the fatigue felt like in this workout. I know that sounds dumb, but the more I can understand and remember how I feel while running, the better I can deal with it and endure it.
It's been awhile since I've run more than a few minutes at 7m/m pace or faster, and I know I've lost some leg strength. I get a fullness/burning feeling mostly in the calves today, but I've felt it in the glutes, hams, and the quads before. I fear this feeling because I believe it's a sign that my legs may give out if I push harder and I might fall off the treadmill or literally just "fall down" from running too hard. Sounds dumb, but true, and I need to work on pushing through that.
The other feeling, and this is the one that really gets me and I know I'm close to slowing down or stopping... is the tiredness of breathing. My diaphragm gets tired of breathing in rhythm to my stride, and I start breathing faster, which in turn relaxes me in a way that makes me lose my core stability, and then my stride probably gets out of whack.

Also, did I warm up well enough? I did 5m at 10m/m pace then some dynamic stretching and a brief stride at 7m/m. Should I actually run a bit more? Daniels thinks you should run hard fro 2 to 3 minutes 10 minutes before a race. Maybe I should do that.
I can tell that my stride is changing. Last Saturday I went to the track and shot video of my easy pace. I was astonished to see how badly my left foot pronated on foot/ground impact, plus it was right underneath my center of gravity and pigeoned out a bit (I'm now convinced that this had everything to do with my plantar fascitis). I've corrected that by using my hip abductors to fix the pidgeon toe which in turn plants my foot more to the left of my center of gravity. The consequence is that I'm using more of the outside of my glutes and hams... are very sore, even when I walk!
I believe once the soreness goes away I can focus on enduring the breathing fatigue.

I said last week that I was going to do the double tabata today, and I did it: 12% incline, 9mph, 8 rounds of 20:10, rest 20 min, then another 8 rounds.
After the first 8 rounds, I literally said under my breath, "I'm scared!" because I couldn't believe that it was still that hard even after the number of times I've been able to complete the 8. I've had a bit of inflammation in my throat, a cough, just north of the bronchials, and I could taste blood after I was done. The pain from that was probably making my chest pain worse. You know the sensation you get when you've been outside working out in really cold weather; your throat and chest just kill! That's how it felt. My HR was hovering around 100bpm and I just couldn't get it to come down. Plus I felt a little weak, like I should just stop, hang up the shoes call it a day...
I waited for about 20min and then started. I knew from my past few experiences that after the first 20sec round my heart would be jumping out of my chest during the 10sec rest, and sure enough it was. But strangely the cough went away completely and the pain sensation was mostly tied to my legs and fatigue; I felt "warmed up". I knew if I could get to 6, then I might have a chance and finish all 8. 6 left my legs feeling like I "tied up", 7 felt worse and the top of my head felt oddly cold, and 8 felt just like the 8th on the first tabata I'd done a few weeks back.
I completed it.
It's been about two hours since I finished the workout, and I feel fine, but I got tired walking to the water cooler and back to my desk... and my cough is back. I wonder what I just did.
1 Day Later:
Almost drank too much coffee this morning. Really tired, but I've eaten well and have drunk at least a gallon of water so far (3pm). I think I'm recovering well. Chest is definitely tired, and my throat is a bit worse today. No DOMS, but I might get that tomorrow. Resting HR has been around 49bpm.

The goal of this protocol is to elicit 400m race conditions without going full speed. First two intervals didn't feel that hard, however not having much practice at 5mm pace made me feel a bit jerky. I focused on maintaining a stable core and turning over the legs. Next two were a bit harder, with the last really putting on the burn with 30sec to go. At one point I felt my glutes give way which made me fee like my knees were giving out, increasing leg turnover, and made my hamstrings work harder; man did they burn!
Immediate recovery went well. Earlier in the year when I would do a tabata, i'd feel like death for awhile, but now I think I'm adapting. Even my warmup mile (which sometimes ends with .10 at 5m/m) feels really easy.

After I warmed up with 50GM and light stretching I decided to star the run, but after a mile and a half my leg started to numb up. Stretching didn't help, so I decided a new tactic would be 130lb near straight leg deadlifts. Yesterday's workout taught me that if I stretch way too much, then I can't jump up and down vigorously as the impaired facet joint was too loose. They seem to do the trick. I could run a mile and leg and back felt very alive, no numbness.
Remember: Strength drives stamina drives endurance. From now on I'm going to warmup with GMs then deadlift to really strengthen the back... then run.

First week on milk I could never get to sleep at night. I thought it might be overtraining or too much coffee, but it may have been too many vitamins. Second week of milk was fine.
